[3] Challenges: Battle against Ebola in Congo pits medical hope against local chaos
Date: Tue 27 Nov 2018
[New York Times, abridged, edited]
https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/27/health/ebola-outbreak-congo.html
[Byline: Donald G McNeil Jr]

The battle against Ebola now underway in central Africa is like no other. It is the 1st for which doctors have both a promising vaccine and treatments to offer. These medical innovations are experimental, but the vaccine seems to work well, the 4 new treatments have given preliminary hints of curative powers and a clinical trial of them began [Mon 26 Nov 2018].

It had seemed, with the help of these new tools, that the outbreak was headed for a quick end. Instead, with 419 cases and 240 deaths, it is now the 2nd deadliest ever (although the 2014 West African one was orders of magnitude larger, with over 28 000 cases and 11 000 deaths).

Dr Peter Salama, the WHO's emergency response chief, recently said he expected this outbreak to last at least another 6 months. That's because it is unique in another way: it's the 1st to erupt in an area rived by gun battles. Doctors and other experts currently or formerly working in the region described a landscape that is not quite a war zone but in which shooting can break out almost anywhere for unknown reasons.

The traumatized population is a mix of local residents, 4 million internally displaced people and 500 000 refugees from other countries. They speak many languages and often distrust outsiders -- including the national government and its army and police.

Some residents refuse to believe that Ebola exists or dismiss it as a foreign plot to test new medicines on Africans. Many simply see it as a lesser threat than the constant ones: malaria, cholera, hunger, and violence.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This article is worth reading to gain further understanding of the difficulty in fighting the current Ebola outbreak and why it will be so difficult to control. - Mod.LK

----------------------
[4] Response. Butembo: an intense mobilization of women against the transmission of Ebola
Date: Tue 27 Nov 2018
Source: Radio Moto Butembo-Beni [in French, machine trans., edited]
http://radiomotofm.info/lirearticle.php?billet=5116


Butembo women's organizations held a press briefing on Tue 27 Nov 2018. This session focused on sensitizing women to stop the chain of transmission of the Ebola virus disease. One of the meeting rooms of the Welcome Center Joli RÃªve was the setting for this meeting with the press.

During her presentation, Ms Cathy Furaha advised all women to be on maximum alert if a suspicious case arises around them. This, for referral to the nearest health facility or Ebola treatment center, ETC, for prompt management. "We are asking all women to monitor everyone in the community who has signs and symptoms of the disease and refer them to the nearest health facility or Ebola treatment center. If we get to the ETC quickly, we have 80 percent survival," she said, adding that the ETC is the only place in the world where there are 4 types of treatment for Ebola.

It should be noted that these women in Butembo say they have become aware that they are more vulnerable in this epidemic since they are close to the sick.

--
